            Brain-computer interfaces (BCIs) are achieving the goal that we only dreamt of being possible. The idea of creating a link between the human mind and external devices has now become a reality thanks to advancements in neuroengineering and computational neuroscience (Kumar et al., 2025). The definition of brain-computer interface is a system that establishes direct communication between the brain and an external device (López-Larraz, 2020). The main purpose of BCIs is to help patients who have communication and motor function impairments due to conditions like amyotrophic lateral sclerosis (ALS), stroke and spinal cord injury (Awuah Wireko et al., 2024). However, it isn’t limited to only restoring motor functions as it can be used for entertainment purposes as well such as creating immersive experiences for video games, virtual reality, determining user’s emotions and for assessing fatigue for attention-demanding jobs such as air traffic controllers or truck drivers (University of Calgary, n.d.). Currently a real-world example of BCIs today is Neuralink. Neuralink has already started the development of BCIs and has been granted approval by the FDA for human clinical trials. Their first patient, Noland Arbaugh is a quadriplegic which means paralysed from all four limbs, had a successful operation in February 2024. He was the first person to be implanted with a BCI chip and was showcased playing a game of chess and Mario Cart using only his thoughts (Kokot, 2025).
        </p>
