        <h2 class="mb-3">2. How does it work?</h2>

        <p>
            A brain-computer interface(BCI) works by interpreting the electrochemical signals that occur when a thought or decision is made. These signals occur at the synapses between neurons. BCIs capture this information using electrodes that are attached near neurons where it measures voltage and frequency and the intensity of neural spikes (Dam, 2025). A brain-computer interface (BCI) usually consists of three main parts: a device to measure brain activity, a computer to analyse and process the recorded brain activity, and lastly, a device or application to control. The device to measure brain activity can be a small brain chip, cap, headband or headset which has specially designed sensors to detect and record signals from the brain usually using methods such as EEG. The signal is then interpreted by a computer which uses specialised processing methods to try and decode the user’s desired action from the brain signal. The last part is to complete the task that the user intends to complete by sending the signal to the device or application (University of Calgary, n.d.).
        </p>

