    <!-- Section 3: Types of BCI -->
    <section>
        <h2 class="mb-3">3. Types of BCI</h2>

        <p>
            There are different types of techniques for recording brain activity. It can be measured using electroencephalography (EEG), magnetoencephalography (MEG), functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI), microelectrode arrays (MEAs), and electrocorticography (ECoG) (Dam, 2025). The type of technique is determined by the type of BCI being used. The two different types of BCIs are Non-Invasive and Invasive. Non-invasive BCIs can monitor the brain without surgery by using methods like EEG, MEG, or fMRI (Dam, 2025). Non-invasive BCIs are cheaper and safer due to no surgery required however they suffer with low resolution of data which results in limited applications and motor recovery (Nicolas-Alonso & Gomez-Gil, 2012)(University of Calgary, n.d.). EEG uses electrodes that are placed on the scalp to measure electrical activity. It is widely used due to its portability, affordability and good level of temporal resolution. MEG produces better resolution than EEG but requires specialised environments as it isn’t portable and it detects the brain's magnetic fields. fMRI measures the blood flow in the brain to deduce neural activity. It offers a high level of temporal resolution but cannot be used in real time due to slow signal processing (Dam, 2025). Invasive BCIs on the other hand, monitors the brain by undergoing surgery to implant them and uses the method of MEA or ECoG. Invasive BCIs have a direct connection to electrodes which possess’ high accuracy and level of temporal resolution but have significant risks due to scar tissue formation (Awuah Wireko et al., 2024). These BCIs are costly due to the surgical costs, but researchers agree this type of BCIs can be used to restore movement through prostheses due to the high level of temporal resolution in the readings of brain activity (Nicolas-Alonso & Gomez-Gil, 2012). MEA uses small electrodes placed in the cortex of the brain to track neuron activity. This is mainly used for controlling robotic limbs and neuroprosthesis. ECoG uses electrodes placed directly on the surface of the brain. This allows for a high level of accuracy and resolution of readings while reducing some risks associated with deeper implants (Nicolas-Alonso & Gomez-Gil, 2012)(University of Calgary, n.d.).
        </p>

